<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1565,2031]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,408,1565,1591]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
It is not presently possible to assign a female from the Salzburg province, 
<collectingCountry box="[1295,1381,1565,1591]" name="Austria" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Austria</collectingCountry>
(see below) to any of the currently recognized species of 
<taxonomicName box="[761,878,1605,1630]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[761,878,1605,1630]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paradelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The possibility exists though, that it belongs to an unrecognized species of 
<taxonomicName box="[486,603,1645,1670]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[486,603,1645,1670]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paradelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described from the nearby Styria province by 
<bibRefCitation author="Karl" box="[1172,1313,1645,1671]" pageId="13" pageNumber="24" refString="Karl, O. (1943) Erganzungen und Berichtigungen zu meiner Arbeit uber die Musciden (Prof. Dr. Fr. Dahl, Die Tierwelt Deutschlands, Teil 13) VI. Stettiner Entomologische Zeitung, 104, 64 - 77." type="journal article" year="1943">
Karl (
<number box="[1243,1304,1645,1671]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1943.0">1943</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
under the name 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" box="[222,449,1685,1710]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomyia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpestris">
<emphasis box="[222,449,1685,1710]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Pegomyia alpestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It was based on 
<specimenCount box="[656,736,1685,1711]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="male">
<number box="[656,671,1685,1711]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1.0">1</number>
male
</specimenCount>
taken in the subalpine zone of Admonter Kalbling, Styrian Alps. The 
<typeStatus box="[276,379,1725,1751]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">holotype</typeStatus>
was probably lost during WW 
<number box="[748,762,1725,1751]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2.0">2</number>
, but Karl’s drawing of the male hypopygium (
<figureCitation box="[1313,1399,1725,1751]" captionStart="FIGURES 54, 55" captionStartId="35.[151,269,641,665]" captionTargetBox="[300,1274,189,602]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[281,1305,168,617]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 54, 55. Paradelia alpestris, male. 54. Sternite V, ventral view. 55. Hypopygium, caudal view. (After Karl, 1943.)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273928/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[1369,1399,1725,1751]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="55.0">55</number>
</figureCitation>
) is unmistakably of a 
<taxonomicName box="[369,486,1765,1790]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[369,486,1765,1790]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paradelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hennig" box="[501,733,1765,1791]" pageId="13" pageNumber="23" refString="Hennig, W. (1972) Anthomyiidae [part]. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region, 7 (1), Lief. 294, 425 - 472. E. Schweizerbart, Stuttgart." type="journal article" year="1972">
Hennig (
<number box="[604,668,1765,1791]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1972.0">1972</number>
: 
<number box="[679,725,1765,1791]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="435.0">435</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
treated Karl’s species as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunneonigra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">P. brunneonigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but I disagree with that synonymy based on certain aspects in the original description: (
<number box="[1216,1228,1805,1831]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1.0">1</number>
) a body length of 
<quantity box="[151,215,1845,1871]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" unit="mm" value="5.0">5mm</quantity>
; (
<number box="[237,253,1845,1871]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="2.0">2</number>
) a densely grey-dusted abdomen without a distinct mid-dorsal dark stripe; and (
<number box="[1205,1220,1845,1871]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="3.0">3</number>
) a sternite V with non-projecting posterior lobes. Karl’s original drawing of sternite V (
<figureCitation box="[958,1044,1885,1911]" captionStart="FIGURES 54, 55" captionStartId="35.[151,269,641,665]" captionTargetBox="[300,1274,189,602]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[281,1305,168,617]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 54, 55. Paradelia alpestris, male. 54. Sternite V, ventral view. 55. Hypopygium, caudal view. (After Karl, 1943.)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273928/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[1013,1044,1885,1911]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="54.0">54</number>
</figureCitation>
) is also difficult to reconcile with that of 
<taxonomicName box="[239,431,1925,1950]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunneonigra">
<emphasis box="[239,431,1925,1950]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">P. brunneonigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[450,541,1925,1951]" captionStart="FIGURES 65 – 68" captionStartId="38.[151,269,1260,1284]" captionTargetBox="[188,1400,224,1223]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[156,1431,194,1237]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 65 – 68. Paradelia brunneonigra, male. 65, 66. Sternite V, lateral and ventral views. 67, 68. Hypopygium, lateral and caudal views. Same scale for 65, 66 and 67, 68 respectively." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/178607/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[508,541,1925,1951]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="66.0">66</number>
</figureCitation>
). Therefore, the possibility exists that 
<taxonomicName authority="Karl" authorityName="Karl" box="[1005,1315,1925,1951]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Paradelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpestris">
<emphasis box="[1005,1234,1925,1950]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Paradelia alpestris</emphasis>
(Karl)
</taxonomicName>
is a valid species of the Austrian Alps but currently unrecognized in the male sex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
